  "prompt": "How do laser mice work?",
  "response": "Laser mice use an optical sensor with a laser to track movement across a surface. Here's a basic overview of how they work:\n\n1. Laser Light Emission\n- A small laser diode emits a laser beam onto the surface\n- The laser typically uses an infrared or near-infrared wavelength\n\n2. Surface Reflection\n- The laser light reflects off microscopic irregularities in the surface\n- Different surfaces reflect light differently\n\n3. Image Capture\n- A small camera or sensor underneath the mouse captures successive images of the surface\n- These images are taken many times per second (typically 1000-6000 times)\n\n4. Movement Calculation\n- A digital signal processor compares consecutive images\n- It calculates the difference between images to determine movement direction and speed\n- This information is translated into cursor movement on the screen\n\n5. Resolution and Tracking\n- Laser mice typically have higher resolution (DPI) than optical mice\n- They can track movement on more surface types, including glossy or uneven surfaces\n- More advanced sensors provide more precise tracking\n\nThis technology allows precise cursor control and movement tracking across different surfaces, making laser mice more versatile and accurate compared to older tracking technologies.",
